<span id="freeTextContainer16109546931396162392">Second reading. I have no memory of the first, which is unusual for me. <br/><br/>In “House of the Sleeping Beauties” an elderly man frequents a house near the sea where he sleeps with attractive young unclothed women who’ve been heavily sedated. <br/><br/>In “One Arm” a man borrows a girlfriend’s limb for the night and takes it to his room where he tries it on for size; it talks to him and comments on the decor. <br/><br/>In “Of Birds and Bees,” an animal fancier, perhaps unintentionally, kills many birds and dogs in pursui</span>
  <span id="freeText16109546931396162392" style="display:none">Second reading. I have no memory of the first, which is unusual for me. <br /><br />In “House of the Sleeping Beauties” an elderly man frequents a house near the sea where he sleeps with attractive young unclothed women who’ve been heavily sedated. <br /><br />In “One Arm” a man borrows a girlfriend’s limb for the night and takes it to his room where he tries it on for size; it talks to him and comments on the decor. <br /><br />In “Of Birds and Bees,” an animal fancier, perhaps unintentionally, kills many birds and dogs in pursuit of a kind of lonely oneness with nature.</span>
