<div id="review_3760756152" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3760756152" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3143117-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1571421692p2/3143117.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3760756152?book_show_action=true">Jan 09, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/3143117-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780525434139" href="/book/show/34626038-house-of-the-sleeping-beauties-and-other-stories">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=biblioteca">biblioteca</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=nobel-prize">nobel-prize</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3143117-david?shelf=japanese">japanese</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3760756152" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11071608957705474193">Back at university I studied the Ancient Greek and Latin romance novel. One of the leitmotifs used was the comparison of beautiful women in the storyline to flowers. Yes, our western idea of eros is tied to these images.<br/><br/>This is where the comparison ends. In the main short story, “House of the Sleeping Beauties” beautiful women and flower images are used to contrast the aging narrator Eguchi (67 years old). The old man goes to bed with beautiful sleeping women (yes, it sounds creepy). But the con</span>
  <span id="freeText11071608957705474193" style="display:none">Back at university I studied the Ancient Greek and Latin romance novel. One of the leitmotifs used was the comparison of beautiful women in the storyline to flowers. Yes, our western idea of eros is tied to these images.<br /><br />This is where the comparison ends. In the main short story, “House of the Sleeping Beauties” beautiful women and flower images are used to contrast the aging narrator Eguchi (67 years old). The old man goes to bed with beautiful sleeping women (yes, it sounds creepy). But the contrast is nothing nice. Aging sucks. A smell or image evokes a memory and he relives his past. Not everything he did was good. What can you say for a guy visiting, in every other sense, is a brothel (and yet it’s not)? Remember, flowers, like beauty, die.<br /><br />The language is beautiful, erotic, enticing and evocative. He teases us as there is a dark side. Borges? Definitely not the “romance” novel as we know it. Published in 1961 it was inspirational for Gabriel Garcia Márquez.<br /><br />“One Arm” (1964) tells the very surreal story of a woman who removes her arm and gives it as a gift for a male friend. He takes the arm home. I kid you not. The symbolism seems to be the underlying relationship between men and women. It was definitely odd.<br /><br />I quite liked the older tale in the trio. “Of Birds and Beasts” (1933) tells the story of a man who prefers animals to people, because people are cruel and nasty. He raises song birds and dogs to sell but oddly, raising the animals presents challenges. One day, a male bird escapes leaving the female alone. He can’t buy a single bird and is forced to buy a pair. When he adds the couple to the single bird, discord happens and in the end, he finds a dead bird. Which one died of the two females? Who killed who? Ah, the savage animal world.<br /><br />On top of this, he has this on going relationship with an old flame, Chikako. She performs a traditional Japanese dance, but her age is showing in her routine. Then he meets her musical accompanist. It is a cruel world.<br /><br />A special thanks to Nikos for pointing me to this writer. Such a different sensibility.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11071608957705474193" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


