    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1434295342" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1434295342" />
    <a title="Stephen P(who no longer can participate due to illness)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11602286-stephen-p-who-no-longer-can-participate-due-to-illness"><img alt="Stephen P(who no longer can participate due to illness)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1461732018p2/11602286.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1434295342?book_show_action=true">Nov 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephen P(who no longer can participate due to illness)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephen P(who no longer can participate due to illness)" href="/user/show/11602286-stephen-p-who-no-longer-can-participate-due-to-illness">Stephen P(who no longer can participate due to illness)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11602286-stephen-p-who-no-longer-can-participate-due-to-illness?shelf=short-story">short-story</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1434295342" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12670156011438401140">(The first and title story of this small collection.)<br/><br/>The ethereal bonded with the objections. And yet…yet…<br/><br/>Young virginal women drugged into submissive sleep. Elderly impotent men visiting to sleep by them. Women objectified as passive helpless beings there for the gratification of men. Men objectified as maleness defined by sex.<br/><br/>Can the content of a work disable the reception, offhanded erase the esthetic accomplishments. Works that come to mind is Ahab and Moby Dick, Winkler’s Natura Morta, What</span>
  <span id="freeText12670156011438401140" style="display:none">(The first and title story of this small collection.)<br /><br />The ethereal bonded with the objections. And yet…yet…<br /><br />Young virginal women drugged into submissive sleep. Elderly impotent men visiting to sleep by them. Women objectified as passive helpless beings there for the gratification of men. Men objectified as maleness defined by sex.<br /><br />Can the content of a work disable the reception, offhanded erase the esthetic accomplishments. Works that come to mind is Ahab and Moby Dick, Winkler’s Natura Morta, What I’ve heard about, The Tunnel.<br /><br />Kawabata’s prose is located in dreamy wisps, sighs of sensuality, sentiment without toeing over the tinged line into sentimentality. When literature works, these sighed dreamy wisps congeal with the content each supporting and furthering the other. If at disparate odds, intended or not, it seems that one highlights the other in its discord. A certain tension is built. In this book the ineffable vanishing prose mingles with the brute song of an aged man groping his way through the cobwebs of memory.<br /><br />What about the present? The moments now that are slipping by. Small moments appear seeming he wants the moment to be more than the fraught distortions of the past. Wants these young women whose faces are often hid by their fallen hair or their backs curled toward him, to awake?<br /><br />Death can arrive in its unexpected suddenness or a drawn spite of suffering. It’s not considered, the gradual fade of age as the horizon cast over the plains of sand clarifies itself in outline, hues and shades of color dulling. This also is the map Kawabata draws. This trod toward death now matched with awareness and its gradual understanding. No leniency to slow the pace. The remaining alternative resides within the imagination of memory. <br /><br />This is a gently sad tale. Kawabata finds the honed level of voice and mood to cut through to the much avoided scraped scrags of life’s experience. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12670156011438401140" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


