<span id="freeTextContainer8070557989609322607">3.75 stars<br/><br/>Some months ago last year I came across its seemingly pricey hardcover at the DASA BookCafe in Bangkok and couldn&apos;t make up my mind to buy it due to its unfamiliar title by Kawabata. When I made a call a few days later, it&apos;s a bit disappointing to know that it was already reserved/sold via a call. So it&apos;s my delight to see it on the bookshelf in a large bookstore last month with its reasonable price. <i>House of the Sleeping Beauties</i> is the first story first published as &quot;<i>Nemureru bijo</i>&quot; (</span>
  <span id="freeText8070557989609322607" style="display:none">3.75 stars<br /><br />Some months ago last year I came across its seemingly pricey hardcover at the DASA BookCafe in Bangkok and couldn't make up my mind to buy it due to its unfamiliar title by Kawabata. When I made a call a few days later, it's a bit disappointing to know that it was already reserved/sold via a call. So it's my delight to see it on the bookshelf in a large bookstore last month with its reasonable price. <i>House of the Sleeping Beauties</i> is the first story first published as "<i>Nemureru bijo</i>" (Kodansha, 1961); Other Stories being <i>One Arm</i> first published as "<i>Kataude</i>" (Kodansha, 1964) and <i>Of Birds and Beasts</i> first published as "<i>Kinju</i>" (Kodansha, 1933). (p. 4) Taken his birthyear 1899 into account, Yasunari Kawabata wrote the first story, the second and the third when he was 62, 65 and 34 respectively.<br /><br />I found reading his first story arguably enjoyable, better than the other two of course; a factor, I think, might have been due to his age at 62 presumably mature with literary stature and experience that decisively shape his unique plot and imagination. However, I wonder how he can find or achieve any "reality" as mentioned in the Goodreads synopsis from such girls, that is, from those selected beauties sleeping not naturally but by means of sleeping pills administered by the old woman with a few automatic responses to the man who pays for their time and intimacy at night in the house. Interestingly, the anonymous old man has paid for three beauties of different ages so that he can closely observe each one to his heart's content and sleep with her till the morning -- but not touch her -- in the intervals of a week or two.<br /><br />To continue . . .</span>
