<div id="review_491477066" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/491477066" />
    <a title="April" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10478000-april"><img alt="April" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621463389p2/10478000.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/491477066?book_show_action=true">Jan 01, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="April" class="user" itemprop="url" name="April" href="/user/show/10478000-april">April</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10478000-april?shelf=short-story-or-stories">short-story-or-stories</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer491477066" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5887851048159496884">*&apos;Other stories&apos; discounted.<br/><br/>I wanted to enjoy this novel far more, I really did. It’s a rarity when I’m not overly impressed with a piece of Japanese fiction, but yes; it happened.<br/><br/>Expressed with fragility and reminiscent, I feel, of Robert Browning’s <i>Porphyria’s Lover</i>, <i>The House of Sleeping Beauties</i> seems to flow like a stream of still images taken directly from a camera; each with a harmonious sanctity about them, as if Kawabata has aligned a row of somewhat mental mannequins. Each ‘sleeping be</span>
  <span id="freeText5887851048159496884" style="display:none">*'Other stories' discounted.<br /><br />I wanted to enjoy this novel far more, I really did. It’s a rarity when I’m not overly impressed with a piece of Japanese fiction, but yes; it happened.<br /><br />Expressed with fragility and reminiscent, I feel, of Robert Browning’s <i>Porphyria’s Lover</i>, <i>The House of Sleeping Beauties</i> seems to flow like a stream of still images taken directly from a camera; each with a harmonious sanctity about them, as if Kawabata has aligned a row of somewhat mental mannequins. Each ‘sleeping beauty’ seems to be caught between two worlds; in a liminal state of being too distant to draw back and frozen within the present (which, might I add, is the main ‘selling point’ for these male visitors). I wanted to find it beautiful; truly, a surreal and mind-turning narrative which I typically affiliate with Japanese fiction, but my main problem with this short is the disturbing treatment of the girls themselves, and the bordering on abuse/necrophilia themes. I’ve never considered myself much of a feminist at all, but I was deeply disturbed by the objectifying of the ‘beauties,’ which is odd considering I’ve sifted through dozens of Japanese novels with similar treatment of female characters and bear no ill will to somewhat differing-from-the-norm themes (for example; many titles I’ve read and enjoyed in the past strike a ‘different chord,’ shall we say, mainly that of of Mann’s <i>Death in Venice</i> and parts of Nabokov’s <i>Lolita.</i>) Their ‘doll-like’ projection was deeply unnerving for me and even more so by the fact that they could quite easily be assigned suicide partners for whatever older gentlemen decided to depart from this world, providing he was a trusting customer. Kawabata has crafted something quite illuminating, however, and dare I say ‘special’ in its own right, despite not suiting my tastes at all. An effective story – if for the wrong reasons. Slightly disappointed by this book.<br /><br />**Originally awarded a two star rating but subsequently ‘bumped it up’ to a three after further thought.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5887851048159496884" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


