    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1390619988" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1390619988" />
    <a title="Billy O&#39;Callaghan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4181062-billy-o-callaghan"><img alt="Billy O&#39;Callaghan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623422302p2/4181062.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1390619988?book_show_action=true">Sep 13, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Billy O&#39;Callaghan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Billy O&#39;Callaghan" href="/user/show/4181062-billy-o-callaghan">Billy O&#39;Callaghan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4181062-billy-o-callaghan?shelf=around-the-world">around-the-world</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4181062-billy-o-callaghan?shelf=nobel-prize">nobel-prize</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1390619988" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1832782946705986845">In this collection&apos;s title novella, an old man named Eguchi visits, on the recommendation of a friend, an exclusive brothel that accommodates a strange fetish: for those who have gone beyond the passions of manhood, the opportunity to sleep alongside a beautiful young virgin. Touching is permitted, but only within reason, but this is about illusion (or delusion) and a way for those approaching an end to relive again, in their minds and senses, the splendors of youth.<br/>Deluged with flashbacks of ol</span>
  <span id="freeText1832782946705986845" style="display:none">In this collection's title novella, an old man named Eguchi visits, on the recommendation of a friend, an exclusive brothel that accommodates a strange fetish: for those who have gone beyond the passions of manhood, the opportunity to sleep alongside a beautiful young virgin. Touching is permitted, but only within reason, but this is about illusion (or delusion) and a way for those approaching an end to relive again, in their minds and senses, the splendors of youth.<br />Deluged with flashbacks of old romances and love affairs, Eguchi is in equal parts thrilled and disturbed by the experience. In the following weeks he is drawn back again and again, each time getting to sleep beside a different heavily drugged young girl, a different type. He has a secret, too, in that he has not quite reached the senility of impotence, and he attempts over and over to wake his companions, and even contemplates deflowering one of them, though he holds back out of a preservation for purity.<br />This is an incredibly affecting story of the unbridgeable gulf between old age and youth, an existentialist lament of things lost and life spent but a paean also to beauty and vigor. The girls in their eternal sleep are almost unreal, acting as symbols of the beauty, variety and spice of life just as much as flesh-and-blood young women. And yet, on each occasion, with each one being physically different, something of their individualities and maybe even their personalities does shine through. Certainly, for Eguchi, each girl awakens vivid memories and regrets of times and women gone by, and it is this link as much as anything, the women of the past bound in some way with the body in the bed beside him that brings a sense of humanity to what would otherwise be simple perversion.<br />The second story, 'One Arm', is a deeply surreal offering. A young woman gives her arm to a man and allows him to spend the night with it. It's a strange read, quite short with not a lot of plot beyond the basic setup, but it does attempt to address themes of connection, separation, self-loathing, individuality and identity. Interesting, but for me the weakest of the collection's three stories.<br />The book closes with 'Of Birds and Beasts'. An unnamed and clearly depressed man, nearing forty, who, apart from the assistance of a maid, has largely withdrawn from the world of people and who instead surrounds himself with a variety of small animals. In keeping these animals, particularly an array of birds, he claims to find the beauty and wildness of life, but largely through his own carelessness and mishandling, they keep dying on him. And the animals, for all their beauty, and their reliance on him for their survival, are a shield against the world at large and also against having to properly address the regret of missing out on a more fulfilling life with his ex-lover, a dancer and one-time prostitute.<br />I've read a few books of Kawabata's now, and I am just besotted with the stillness and apparent silence and also the unsettling quality of his stories. They boast a kind of millpond tranquility and yet are full of vicious currents, and they continue to churn away in your mind long after you've turned the final page. The writing, too, is just beautiful. With no room for sentimentality, and a quite staunch reserve of surface emotion, his sentences are nevertheless often ripe with pathos and melancholy, and he imbues his texts with the sort of tension that almost defies definition. Questions are asked but left unanswered, the symbolism within the quietly unfolding narrative is left to be felt and reflected on, much as with a great poem or a piece of good music. Such a level of subtlety is what for me makes Kawabata a truly compelling and remarkable writer.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1832782946705986845" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


