<div id="review_1968881824" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1968881824" />
    <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour"><img alt="J.M. Hushour" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442964894p2/17463213.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1968881824?book_show_action=true">Apr 13, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.M. Hushour" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour">J.M. Hushour</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1968881824" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17999341991052134140">It&apos;s been a while since I&apos;ve something as profoundly unsettling and disturbing as &quot;House&quot;. I shouldn&apos;t have been surprised. What couldn&apos;t go awry in a story of a lonely old man who goes to a weird lonely house to sleep naked next to beautiful young naked virgins? I shudder just to recall it.<br/>The edition I read, an older one, had a neat little introduction by Mishima who called &quot;House&quot; constricting and nerve-wracking and he was right. It&apos;s a weird confluence of things that don&apos;t belong together: n</span>
  <span id="freeText17999341991052134140" style="display:none">It's been a while since I've something as profoundly unsettling and disturbing as "House". I shouldn't have been surprised. What couldn't go awry in a story of a lonely old man who goes to a weird lonely house to sleep naked next to beautiful young naked virgins? I shudder just to recall it.<br />The edition I read, an older one, had a neat little introduction by Mishima who called "House" constricting and nerve-wracking and he was right. It's a weird confluence of things that don't belong together: nervous tension and eroticism; horror and purity. That's why Kawabata is a genius.<br />The second story, "One Arm" is almost as wonderfully terrible. A young woman loans a lonely man her arm and he takes it home to bed. What else can I say?<br />The third story, "Of Birds and Beasts" is excellent, if less terrifying in its quiet simplicity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17999341991052134140" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


